summary: I'm still upset they didn't let Sansa stay in the Vale, and prevent her from marrying Ramsay. Like, Sansa charming the lords of...
body:
I’m still upset they didn’t let Sansa stay in the Vale, and prevent her from marrying Ramsay. Like, Sansa charming the lords of the Vale and winning the heart and loyalty of the lord/heir of the Vale as well as the lords and common folk would’ve been a great season 5.

When she eventually marries the lord of the Vale, she would then publicly reveal her identity as Sansa Stark to the Vale and the lords would declare their support for her claim, only then she will write a letter to inform Jon of her plans. She asks Jon to unite the Northern lords for a rebellion against Ramsay rule over their home. Jon agrees and tells Sansa about Rickon being held hostage. Sansa travels to the North and meets Jon and they argue about the fate of Rickon, but constructively work out a battle plan. Littlefinger wanting power, and Sansa, convinces her hubby to hold their entrance in the battle to save Vale lives and convinces the Lord of the Vale to lead the army, but Littlefinger does this so the Lord of the Vale, Sansa’s husband, can die first in the battle. Battle of the Bastards begin, Sansa is horrified b/c her army has yet to come and Jon might die, Sansa gives up hope, Vale Knights come in the knick of time. Ramsay dies and his wife who he claimed to be Sansa kills him. The Lord of the Vale tells Sansa, injured while alive, of Littlefinger urging him to lead and hold off their army’s entrance, later Sansa let’s Littlefinger know she knows what he wants, in the Godswood. Jon is declared King in the North, despite Sansa being Lady of Winterfell, Littlefinger smirks at her across the hall in a “I told you so” expression. Jon and Sansa reconcile, despite their different veiws of the world, and both agree to rule the North and take out the whitewalkers, while Sansa adds they must also take out the nobles who oppose them [after speaking of Littlefinger haha]. That’s season 6.

No rape, no torture, no unnecessary sibling drama.
